## The surprise that trips up everyone

You learned in 3.1 that calling the setter function updates state and triggers a re-render. That is true. But there is a critical detail that catches everyone off guard, including experienced developers:

**State does not update instantly.**

When you call `setCount(1)`, the variable `count` does not change to `1` right away. It keeps its old value for the rest of that function call. The new value only appears on the **next render**.

### Seeing the problem

```jsx
function BrokenCounter() {
  const [count, setCount] = useState(0);

  function handleClick() {
    setCount(count + 1);
    setCount(count + 1);
    setCount(count + 1);
    // You might expect count to be 3 after this.
    // It will be 1.
  }

  return (
    <button onClick={handleClick}>
      Count: {count}
    </button>
  );
}
```

Why does this only increment by 1? Because all three lines read the same `count` value. When the click happens, `count` is `0`. So all three calls are `setCount(0 + 1)`. You are setting the count to 1 three times in a row.

This is called a **stale closure** -- the function "closes over" the old value of count and does not see the update.

### An analogy

Imagine you are writing on a whiteboard. Someone tells you: "Add 1 to whatever is on the board." You look at the board, see 0, and write down 1. Then they say it again: "Add 1 to whatever is on the board." But you are still reading from a **photograph** of the board taken at the start. The photograph still shows 0. So you write down 1 again.

That is what happens with stale closures. The function has a snapshot of the value from when it was created, not a live view.

### The fix: functional updates

React provides a way to read the latest value instead of the snapshot:

```jsx
function WorkingCounter() {
  const [count, setCount] = useState(0);

  function handleClick() {
    setCount(prev => prev + 1);
    setCount(prev => prev + 1);
    setCount(prev => prev + 1);
    // count will be 3 after re-render
  }

  return (
    <button onClick={handleClick}>
      Count: {count}
    </button>
  );
}
```

Instead of passing a value (`count + 1`), you pass a **function** (`prev => prev + 1`). React calls your function with the most recent value. So:

1. First call: `prev` is `0`, returns `1`
2. Second call: `prev` is `1`, returns `2`
3. Third call: `prev` is `2`, returns `3`

The pattern `prev => prev + 1` is called a **functional update**. When you see it in code, you know the developer needed to read the latest value, not a snapshot.

### When do you need functional updates?

You need functional updates when the new value depends on the old value:

```jsx
// Incrementing -- new value depends on old
setCount(prev => prev + 1);         // YES, use functional

// Toggling -- new value depends on old
setIsOpen(prev => !prev);            // YES, use functional

// Adding to an array -- new value depends on old
setItems(prev => [...prev, newItem]); // YES, use functional

// Setting to a specific value -- no dependency
setName('Alice');                     // NO, just pass the value
setIsLoading(true);                   // NO, just pass the value
```

The rule of thumb: if you are reading the current state to calculate the next state, use a functional update.

## Immutability: the copy-then-change rule

React has a strict rule about updating state that contains objects or arrays: **never modify the existing value. Always create a new one.**

This is called **immutability** -- treating state values as read-only and replacing them with new copies.

### Why? How React detects changes

React decides whether to re-render by checking: "Is the new value a different thing than the old value?" For objects and arrays, React checks if it is the **same reference** (same object in memory), not whether the contents changed.

```jsx
// WRONG -- mutating the existing array
const handleAdd = () => {
  items.push(newItem);  // This modifies the existing array
  setItems(items);      // React sees the same array reference
                        // and thinks nothing changed!
};

// RIGHT -- creating a new array
const handleAdd = () => {
  setItems([...items, newItem]);  // Spread into a new array
                                  // React sees a new reference
                                  // and re-renders!
};
```

The `...` (spread operator) creates a copy. `[...items, newItem]` means: "make a new array with everything from `items`, plus `newItem` at the end."

### Common patterns for immutable updates

**Adding to an array:**
```jsx
setItems([...items, newItem]);
// or at the beginning:
setItems([newItem, ...items]);
```

**Removing from an array:**
```jsx
setItems(items.filter(item => item.id !== idToRemove));
```

**Updating an object:**
```jsx
setUser({ ...user, name: 'New Name' });
// Spread the old object, then override the property you want to change
```

**Updating a nested object:**
```jsx
setUser({
  ...user,
  address: {
    ...user.address,
    city: 'New York'
  }
});
```

Notice the pattern: spread to copy, then override. Every level of nesting needs its own spread.

### Spotting the mutation bug

When you see any of these in React code, it is almost certainly a bug:

```jsx
// These all MUTATE -- they change the existing value
array.push(item);       // Adds to existing array
array.splice(0, 1);     // Removes from existing array
obj.name = 'New';       // Changes existing object property
array.sort();           // Sorts the existing array in-place
array.reverse();        // Reverses the existing array in-place
```

The correct alternatives:

```jsx
// These all create NEW values
[...array, item];                    // New array with item added
array.filter((_, i) => i !== 0);     // New array without first item
{ ...obj, name: 'New' };             // New object with updated name
[...array].sort();                   // Copy first, then sort
[...array].reverse();                // Copy first, then reverse
```

## State batching

One more thing to know: React **batches** state updates that happen in the same event handler. This means if you call multiple setters, React does not re-render after each one -- it waits and does one single re-render with all the changes applied.

```jsx
function handleSubmit() {
  setIsLoading(true);      // Does NOT re-render yet
  setError(null);          // Does NOT re-render yet
  setFormData(data);       // Does NOT re-render yet
  // React re-renders ONCE here, with all three updates
}
```

This is a performance optimization. You do not need to do anything special -- just know that React is smart enough to group updates together.

### Summary of the gotchas

| Gotcha | What happens | The fix |
| :-- | :-- | :-- |
| Stale closure | Reading state in the same function after setting it gives the old value | Use functional update: `prev => prev + 1` |
| Direct mutation | Modifying an object/array without creating a new one -- React does not detect the change | Always spread to copy: `{...obj}`, `[...arr]` |
| Multiple updates | Calling `setValue(value + 1)` multiple times only applies once | Use functional update for each call |

